flowRoot.flowPara: Self-organization is mediated by Hebbian learning, which adjusts connection weights after every saccade. The weights are constrained with divisive post-synaptic weight normalization per projection with learning rate .
Genetic Parvalbumin (PV+) and Somatostatin (Sst+) markers have been essential in disentangling GABAergic interactions in the cortex and linking circuits to function.
Based on the current literature several broad properties can be assigned to PV+ neurons:
• Fast, strong responses, linearly integrating feedforward
and recurrent input1, weakly feature selective,
providing perisomatic inhibition2.
and Sst+ neurons:
• Slow, facilitating responses, recurrently driven,
stronger feature selectivity and dendritic inhibition3.

Here we demonstrate that the fast, feedforward and linear responses of PV+ neurons make them suited to driving local decorrelation and drive map development, while the slower integration and feature selectivity of Sst neurons makes them suited to mediating contextual interactions and gating long-range and feedback input.

A sensitivity analysis was used to determine how the linearity () and hysteresis time constant () of the inhibitory population would affect the development of our model. The effect of these parameters on pinwheel density (ρ), which has been experimentally confirmed to be near π, was assessed. Additionally the map stability and selectivity of different populations was assessed.
Hypercolumn distance is determined by fitting a function to the FFT power spectrum. Pinwheel density (ρ) is the number of pinwheels per hypercolumn.

Results were partitioned into good and bad maps based on a divergence from π pinwheel density (where a good map was defined as ρ=π±0.1). Both linearity of response and a fast time constant were associated with better map quality.
Stability, map quality and selectivity A) over development and B) across contrasts. Demonstrates SEPI model exhibits robust and stable development on par with single population GCAL model.

Effect of inhibitory response linearity on A) mean inhibitory selectivity, B) map stability and C) mean excitatory selectivity. Linear response was associated with low inhibitory selectivity, high stability and high excitatory selectivity.

flowRoot.flowPara: Orientation Tuning curves of a model A) pyramidal, B) Sst and C) PV neuron in the same retinotopic location all displaying contrast invariance. PV neurons have significantly broader tuning due to their persistently higher activity and linear response function.
Based on the known properties of PV+ and Sst+ neurons our model makes multiple predictions.
PV+ neurons:
• Linear integration, strong inputs and low threshold
sufficient to explain broad tuning.
• Essential for robust and stable orientation map
development, due to their ability to locally
decorrelate activity.
Sst+ neurons:
• Facilitating responses and weaker inputs sufficient to
explain sharp tuning.
• Mediate switch from facilitation to suppression
dependent on local contrast, crowded visual scenes
and attentional state.

In this section we will explore how a long-range disynaptic excitatory circuit driving Sst+ neurons can give rise to their orientation and size tuning properties and allows them to mediate a switch from long-range facilitation to suppression.
Detailed time courses demonstrating how long-range interactions can give rise to both facilitation and suppression depending on local contrast.
Low local contrast gives rise to facilitation from the surround, while high local contrast induces strong Sst+ activity, which cancels out surround facilitation and results in net suppression.

Divergent size tuning profiles of PV and Sst neurons. A, B) Reproduced from Adesnik et al. 2012, C) Model size tuning curves. Exponential activation function induces Sst neurons only to respond strongly under strong local stimulation or for large stimuli.
